<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">FBA0019/13-14</span></p><h2 style="line-height:14pt; margin:18pt 0pt 12pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Mazars</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold"> LLP</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">—</span><span style="font-family:Cambria; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence</span></h2><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:10pt 0pt 2pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Taxation of Partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – salaried members</span></h3><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Overall, we believe that the legislation goes far further than the initial consultation might have suggested.  The provisions as they stand make it difficult for anything other than very small partnerships to meet the conditions as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">larger</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> partnerships will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> necessarily have small ‘management’ teams for the partnership as a whole (anything else would be unwieldy) and most performance is measured by reference to business units or departments rather than the whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Larger</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> partnerships treat entry to partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as a very serious matter, as bringing in owners and stewards of a business. It is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">decision neither taken</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> lightly nor based primarily on the factors considered in the draft legislation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is a sense</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the draft legislation is targeted against larg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">er </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">professional firms rather than shutting down perceived abuse</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">this isn’t just going to impact those who have artificially put themselves into partnership structures to benefit from NIC savings but will also impact a number of LLPs who manage progre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssion by having fixed profit share partners who might be involved in the management of their own office or division but who, because of the number of their fellow partners, are not able to demonstrate that they have a role in managing the partnership as a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">whole.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We understand the thinking behind trying to ensure partners have some element of financial risk associated with their membership (the capital contributed condition) but not all partnership members will be able to negotiate these types of financing a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rrangements and by introducing anti avoidance provisions with effect from 5 December, this prevents genuine partnerships from being able to reorganise to prevent their partners being caught by this legislation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that one of the overriding problem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s is that the tax analysis is moving further away from the legal analysis and this is a space where problems often arise. We have now got to a place where partners in large partnerships </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are having</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to put in more capital to avoid being caught by the new rul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es, but if you were say an individual IT provider, providing your services through an LLP to one customer you would now be fine under the new rules. The approach seems to be to try and deal with a perceived problem rather than actually considering the prin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ciples of how partnerships should be taxed.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As the Office of Tax Simplification is reviewing the taxation of partnerships, it would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have been preferable for anti-avoidance measures such as these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be considered in the light of the OTS’ overall recommendat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Now, the fact that the OTS is expected to publish its report in January 2014 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">[</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">interim report published this week</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">] </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">means that the OTS will not have had </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enough time to consider the anti-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">avoidance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> measures properly in context. This risks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at worst</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">validating the work already done by the OTS </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">towards simplifying the taxation of partnerships and at best delaying the process of producing the much-needed reform and simplification of partnership tax.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">draft Finance Bill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposals highlight a systemic p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">roblem in tax legislation. The original idea of removing the automatic presumption of self-employment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for  LLP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> members had the merit of being simple and meeting the requirement of true simplification</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">- </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effectively been stood totally on its head</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The legislation is moving away from providing a level playing field between LLPs and general partnerships. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The reason for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">creating LLPs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the first place was to allow large partnerships to benefit from limited liability but to be treated for tax purposes in the same way as a general partnership.  The ideas proposed now demonstrate clearly that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it is not possible to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> “add simplicity” when </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the need is to remove</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">complexity. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> more constructive approach to reform in this area would have been to involve the OTS in the process of development of the proposals to counter avoidance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. It was not necessary to announce the anti-avoidance provisions in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more than outline but accompany the announcement with anti-forestalling provisions, while then allowing a single, more coherent code of taxation of partnerships, including LLPs, to be developed in a single process.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Creating a distinction for tax purposes n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ow between LLPs and general partnerships means that businesses that chose to operate under an LLP for sound commercial reasons now have disadvantageous tax treatment regardless of the any actual tax avoidance motive.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 14.11pt; padding-left:21.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The provisions in the draft Finance Bil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l 2014 are very widely drafted and will cause many LLPs to have to rethink their funding and profit sharing arrangements to avoid some partne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rs being treated as employees, if these provisions are enacted as currently drafted.  This is despite the fact that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> many of these arrangements have existed for some time and were not set up for tax av</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oidance purposes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Significant changes made between consultation document and draft Finance Bill</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There has been a significant change in the expected scope of these rules b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">etween the consultation document issued on 20 May 2013 and the draft provisions in the Finance Bill. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For example, as regards the provision on ‘disguised employment’, both Conditions A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(‘disguised salary’) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and C </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(capital contribution requirement) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are differ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ent from the proposals in the consultation document.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Section 2.13 of the May consultation document states: </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">These conditions are not intended to apply to members who are in essence partners of a traditional partnership that is now carried on as an LLP. T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">his means they are not intended to affect the status of members who carry on the partnership in common with a view to profit, who take risk in the business and who are to a significant degree rewarded on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">basis of a share in the profits. They are also n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ot intended to affect the status of persons who are taken on as members at an appropriate point in their career in recognition of their professional knowledge and personal skills, and who sacrifice an entitlement to salary in exchange for the opportunity t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">o participate in the business in much the same way as a senior partner, even if as junior partners they are substantially rewarded by a fixed profit share.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This approach has not been followed, and has instead been replaced with detailed mechanical tests w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hich give rise to questions in practice in applying them.  As the consultation period </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for the 2014 Finance Bill </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">closes on 4 February 2014, there is little time for affected LLPs to respond </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to the consultation process </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effectively.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The potential impact of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">making </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> changes o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n how the rules on ‘salaried members’ will apply</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> at a late stage in the legislative process creates uncertainty for affected businesses, means the draft provisions are not properly road tested to check they only counter the perc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eived areas of mischief</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; thus seriously undermining the consultation process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  It also</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> results in affected firms taking whatever remedial action to escape the legislation applying in situations where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it ought never to have applied; creating unnecessary cos</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t and upheaval for businesses. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">          </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">10.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Take, for example, Condition A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: the purpose of this condition is to identify those individuals who do not in reality have rights to the underlying profits of the business, so should not be taxed as self-employed.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The condition is met if at least 80% </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the amounts payable to the individual are in the form of ‘disguised salary’.  Examples of payments which will be caught as disguised salary are fixed sums, payment for piecework, a bonus based on the individual’s own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> performance or just one part of the business, guaranteed profits and non-refundable drawings.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  However, LLPs may have complex arrangements for awarding profits which have nothing whatsoever to do with tax avoidance.  This might include elements of profit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">share representing meeting personal performance targets (eg on winning new work) and the profitability of their own office/ sector, in addition to a share based on the overall success of the business as a whole.  As things stand, a number of these entirely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> commercially driven components of partners’ profits will be caught as ‘disguised salary’.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Indeed, the individual’s profit share may be a share of overall profits but that share will also be affected by personal performance – so where there is a combinati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on of both, there is a lack of clarity and certainty in the provisions as drafted.</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Legislation does not adequately recognise the way business operates.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The draft legislation does not reflect the way partnerships operate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in practice and reflects inadequate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation with business</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to achieve legislation which fulfils its intended purpose without creating negative impact on business which was unforeseen by Parliament</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For example, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Condition B requires a partner to have significant influence over the whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> business to escape in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">order to pass self employed status.  This condition serves no real purpose for LLPs of any size where onl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y a small number of partners can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> exert significant influence over the business as a whole.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  This condition can therefore be rule</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d out for a majority of partners.  Professional partnerships such as Mazars LLP operate with internal accountability at office level, service line level and regional level.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Those partners with responsibility only for a given service line offering in a giv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en office nevertheless are able to commit the firm to contracts and sign out opinions in the firm’s name, for example.  However, as things stand, these very genuine measures of ownership in the business would be insufficient to prevent deemed employment st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">atus on their own, and the individual would also need to pass Condition A or Condition C.  Given the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uncertainties</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> created by Condition A, and the limitations of Condition B, partners are likely to have to fall back on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Condition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> C (capital </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contribution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">).  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This is likely to mean that many individuals have to increase their capital </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contribution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the firm purely to avoid being taxed as employees – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regardless</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the funding requirements of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partnership</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  Indeed, there are good reasons why partnerships may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prefer to be funded largely by bank borrowings as opposed to individual capital contributions, as the latter leaves the firm exposed to repayment when partners leave.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is especially unfortunate that the proposal for members</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> funding should have emerged a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t the same time as HMRC confirming their attitude to cash surpluses in businesses </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for inheritance tax purposes </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(see</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recently published</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ICAEW </span><a href="http://www.icaew.com/~/media/Files/Technical/Tax/Tax%20news/TaxGuides/taxguide-0114-tech-01-14-tax-bpr-and-llps.pdf"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">technical guidance</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that cash surpluses not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">earmarked for specific use</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the business will be excluded from qualifying for business property relief</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Requiring partners to have made a minimum capital contribution in order to obtain se</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lf-employed treatment risks rebuilding the barriers to partnership that took so long to break down and which would threaten to stifle partnerships looking to progress by attracting talent.</span></li></ol><h3 style="line-height:14pt; margin:10pt 0pt 2pt; page-break-after:avoid"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Approach to tax policy making</span></h3><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome in general the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government’s approach to tax policy making, with the consultation process preceding the publication of the draft legislation in December.  This allows representations to be made on the draft legislation prior to the Budget.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 20.19pt; padding-left:15.81pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, whilst the above ambiti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on is welcome, the actual legislation itself still leaves much to be desired in terms of the key aims of clarity, stability and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">predictability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">axpayers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">want </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to have a high degree of certainty over the tax consequences of their actions or proposals, base</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d on the legislation in force.  Sadly, this is not the case.  Too many times, legislation is unclear with the taxpayers needing to fall back on HMRC guidance.  We illustrate this by reference to the Statutory Residence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the General Anti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-Abuse Rule </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in Finance Act 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Statutory Residence Test</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The introduction of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Statutory Residence Test (SRT) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has gone some way towards </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">simplifying what was previously a highly unsatisfactory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">situation that depended too little on legislation and too much on HMRC pr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">actice, resulting in uncertainty for many taxpayers. The process was, however unduly protracted and it did not ultimately produce legislation that meets the ideal of being simple to understand and apply. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is fair to say that the SRT now produces greater </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">certainty for a greater number of taxpayers but there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> situations where the complexity has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significantly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">increased. </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In a matter as straightforward as the layout of the legislation, representations were not heeded: the legislation begins by refe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rring to the first test to be applied as being the “First Automatic UK Test” but the first leg of that test is that the individual does not meet the tests of automatic non-residence.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the “ties” taken into account in determining residence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">new</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> tie has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> been created, that of having one’s “home” or main home in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Both the “old” test and the new take </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">account</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of an individual having accommodation available but that is different from a “home” which is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">very widely defined (Finance Act 2013 Sch. 45 Para.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 25)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">then subject to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">comment in HMRC’s booklet RDR3 which is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> extensive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> but not definitiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, referring only to factor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s that might be taken into account. The result is that nowhere is there a test that a taxpayer can rely on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> An example given by HMRC is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f a mobile home or canal barge but what if the person does not have one such “home” but regularly rents different ones?</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The greatest complexity arises in relation to individuals who work both in the UK and overseas and are required to count </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">days and hours </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of UK and overseas work in different ways for different parts of the tests.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">International journeys can be especially problematical: apart from certain trivial actions that may be disregarded the nature of a journey can have a large bearing on status. For </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">example:</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">travel from a home outside the UK to work here is not relevant at all if no work is done during the journey but if more than a token amount of work is done on the journey, the entire journey counts as work done in the country where the journey beg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">depending on circumstances travel between engagements may or may not count as work, again in the country where the journey begins; and</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 90pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">internationally</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mobile workers need to be able to establish where they were at midnight on any given day</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> since days o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f presence in the UK at midnight are counted when applying the statutory residence test.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition to recording where they are at midnight, the internationally mobile also need to record how many hours’ work they have done and precisely where. For exampl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e, if an individual leaves </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.00 pm on a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seven hour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> flight that is counted as work, perhaps because they are preparing for a meeting at their destination, they may not be counted as present in the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on either the day of departure or the following</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> day but will be treated as having done three hours’ work in the UK on each of those days. The time-recording burden threatens to be extremely onerous.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The end result is that despite the fact that most of the SRT is good and largely fit for purpose, there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are narrow areas of deep uncertainty which are subject to interpretation by HMRC, necessitating the publication of lengthy guides RDR1 and RDR3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which are advisory as to HMRC’s interpretation but do not have any legal force</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Furthermore, despite the involvement of HMRC in the process of developing the SRT from when it was first proposed in the Budget of 2011, initially to come into force in April 2012 but deferred until 2013, guidance on HMRC’s interpretation is still only no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">w coming out. That is not a criticism of the legislative process in narrow terms but it is an indictment of the lack of joining-up between legislature and executive.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">General Anti-Abuse Rule</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> (GAAR)</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The basic test in the GAAR is whether the tax arrangements </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in question can be ‘reasonably regarded as a reasonable course of action in relation to the relevant tax provisions, having regard to all the circumstances…</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.8</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A test requiring a view to be taken on ‘reasonableness’ </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">creates uncertainty </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as different people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have different views on what is reasonable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (and indeed it is necessary for the view itself to be tested as to whether it is reasonably held). </span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.9</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">HMRC has published extensive guidance on the GAAR with detailed examples, but these only scratch the surface of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he issues tax advisers and their clients will have to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">deal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with in practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  The stated objective of the GAAR was to counter ‘egregious’ schemes, but</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re is concern that the HMRC could</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">seek to apply it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> wider in practice.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, there is no cleara</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nce facility </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for taxpayers to gain the required certainty</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  There is likely to be little certainty for taxpayers for several years, until decisions of the Advisory Panel have been published.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.10</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We support the Government’s aim to curb abusive tax schemes, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at the very least providing a clearance facility would have gone some way towards providing comfort to the vast majority of taxpayers who do not engage in abusive tax planning, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">want the assurance that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their proposed actio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ns will not be challenged under</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the GAAR.</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">January 2014</span></p><p style="line-height:14pt; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 54pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt 144pt; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 3pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>